	<div class="abstract-text">
		<h3>Abstract</h3>
		<p>Abnormal undercutting activity (QIDRes) captures informed trading risk as liquidity-providing algorithms compete less to fill marketable orders when adverse selection exposure rises. Unlike existing measures of informed trading risk, daily/intradaily&nbsp;QIDRes&nbsp;is easily constructed for any security with trade and quote data and is uncorrelated with liquidity. When examined around information events,&nbsp;QIDRes&nbsp;behaves similarly to existing measures and predicts arrivals of imminent information events. Moreover, higher&nbsp;QIDRes&nbsp;coincides with weaker subsequent price reversals and increased short-seller and informed institutional-investor activity. Further,&nbsp;QIDRes&nbsp;predicts daily and monthly stock returns, which we attribute to limits-to-arbitrage and informed investors’ order type choices. <P></p>
	</div>
	

